<subSubSection pageNumber="746" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="746">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="746">Note:</emphasis>
Stemmerik (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="746">Blumea</emphasis>
12: 284. 1964) stated that the name was &quot;based on&quot; a Plumier plate (t. 11) and Smith (
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="746">Fl. Vitiensis Nova</emphasis>
2: 269. 1981) accepted this element as the 
<typeStatus>lectotype</typeStatus>
, attributing the choice to Stemmerik. This typification is accepted as dating from 1981. Diaz (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="746">Rev. Jard. Bot. Nac. Univ. Habana</emphasis>
9: 9-13. 1988) reviewed the original elements in detail, reproducing most of the relevant original text and illustrations (f. 1-5), although her conclusion that the later Plumier plate (in Burman, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="746">Pl. Amer</emphasis>
.: t. 227, f. 1. 1760) should be the type is pre-dated by 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Smithâ€™s">Smith's</normalizedToken>
choice.
</paragraph>
